description: From Middle English kitelen, from Old English citelian (“to tickle”), from Proto-West Germanic *kitilōn, from Proto-Germanic *kitilōną, frequentative form of Proto-Germanic *kitōną (“to tickle”), from Proto-Indo-European *geid- (“to stick, jab, tickle”).

Cognate with Dutch kittelen, kietelen (“to tickle”), Low German kettelen, ketelen (“to tickle”), German kitzeln (“to tickle”), Icelandic kitla (“to tickle”), Swedish kittla, kittsla, Danish kilde and perhaps Old Armenian կիծ- (kic-, “to sting, bite”). Compare tickle.

entries.meaning: (Scotland and Northern England) Not easily managed

verbs.description: kittle (third-person singular simple present kittles, present participle kittling, simple past and past participle kittled)

entries.meaning: (transitive, Scotland and Northern England) To tickle, to touch lightly.

description: From Middle English kitelen, from Old Norse kjetla (“to bring forth young”), equivalent to kit +‎ -le.

verbs.description: kittle (third-person singular simple present kittles, present participle kittling, simple past and past participle kittled)

entries.meaning: (intransitive, Scotland and Northern England) To bring forth young, as a cat; to kitten; to litter.
